snippet.textDisplay: Regarding Steam and allegations of antitrust/monopoly, I can see that being decided in a similar way to allegations of the NFL behaving similarly by the ill-fated AFL; that being, 'natural monopolies' occasionally arise in markets requiring high initial capital investment and can be sticky due to brand recognition. In short, they'll technically win, but will win $1 in legal costs. Natural monopolies are indeed a regrettable result of our markets, but it's rare that they've actually broken laws in the course of attaining that dominant market position.

New York charges $15 fee to ISPs to provide broadband for poor people, which mean ISPs in turn will still ADVERTISE the same rates but will have an asterisk next to the price (very small one) with no specifics other than "additional fees and taxes may apply"  however when you get bill they'll be sure to be very specific and line item that charge.
